## Step 2: According to the properties of the cross product, we can expand the expression as follows:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 6(3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) - 7(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \\
&= 18\mathbf{c} + 6\mathbf{a} - 14\mathbf{b} + 7\mathbf{a} \\
&= (18\mathbf{c} - 14\mathbf{b}) + 13\mathbf{a}
\end{align*}

## Step 3: Now, we will substitute the given values for $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b},$ $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c},$ and $\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}$ into the expression:
\begin{align*}
(18\mathbf{c} - 14\mathbf{b}) + 13\mathbf{a} &= 18\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} - 14\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} + 13\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

## Step 4: By calculating the cross product of $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{b}$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{b} &= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{vmatrix}
\mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\
4 & 7 & 2 \\
1 & -7 & 18
\end{vmatrix} \\
&= (126 - (-28)) \mathbf{i} - (72 - 2 \cdot 18) \mathbf{j} + (-28 - 7 \cdot 1) \mathbf{k} \\
&= 154 \mathbf{i} - 64 \mathbf{j} - 35 \mathbf{k}
\end{align*}

## Step 4: We can start by finding $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} &= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}, \\
\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} &= \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 5: Then, we can find $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} &= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 14 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 10: We can start by calculating $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} &= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= 4a_1 + 7a_2 + 2a_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 11: Similarly, we can calculate $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} &= \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= 6a_1 - 7a_2 + 3a_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 12: Now we can substitute these expressions for $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}$ into the expression $(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) \times \mathbf{a}.$
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) \times \mathbf{a} &= (\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 14 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}) \times \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} -2a_1 + 14a_2 - a_3 \\ -2a_2 + 14a_3 + a_1 \\ -2a_3 + 14a_1 + a_2 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 12: Now we can calculate $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} &= \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 14 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= (4a_1 + 7a_2 + 2a_3) - (6a_1 - 7a_2 + 3a_3).
\end{align*}

## Step 13: After simplifying the expression, we get:
\begin{align*}
(6 - 4)\mathbf{a} + (-7 + 7)\mathbf{b} + (3 - 3)\mathbf{c} + 1 \cdot \mathbf{a} = \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 13: We can start by finding the dot product of $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{a}:$
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) \cdot \mathbf{a} &= \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) \\
&= 6a_1 - 7a_2 + 3a_3 - (14a_1 + 7a_2 - a_3) \\
&= -8a_1 - 10a_2 + 4a_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 14: We can start by finding $\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} c_1 \\ c_2 \\ c_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= c_1 - 7c_2 + 18c_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 15: Similarly, we can find $\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= a_1 - 7a_2 + 18a_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 15: Similarly, we can calculate $\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= a_1 - 7a_2 + 18a_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 16: We can start by finding $\mathbf{c} \cdot \mathbf{a}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{c} \cdot \mathbf{a} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= a_1 - 7a_2 + 18a_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 18: We can start by finding $\mathbf{c} \cdot \mathbf{a}:$
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{c} \cdot \mathbf{a} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= a_1 - 7a_2 + 18a_3.
\end{align*}

## Step 15: We can now simplify the expression $(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) \times \mathbf{a}:$
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) \times \mathbf{a} &= ( \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 14 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} ) \times \begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\
-2 & 14 & -1 \\
a_1 & a_2 & a_3 \end{vmatrix} \\
&= \mathbf{i}\begin{vmatrix} 14 & -1 \\ a_2 & a_3 \end{vmatrix} - \mathbf{j}\begin{vmatrix} -2 & -1 \\ a_1 & a_3 \end{vmatrix} + \mathbf{k}\begin{vmatrix} -2 & 14 \\ a_1 & a_2 \end{vmatrix} \\
&= (14a_3 + a_2)\mathbf{i} - (-2a_3 - a_1)\mathbf{j} + (-2a_2 - 14a_1)\mathbf{k}
\end{align*}

## Step 7: Substituting the values we know, we have:
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) \times \mathbf{a} &= (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{c} - (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b})\mathbf{a} \\
&= \mathbf{c} - 14\mathbf{a}
\end{align*}

## Step 7: Using the given values, we can calculate the dot products:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} &= 1, \\
\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} &= -14.
\end{align*}

## Step 6: Now, we can use the result to simplify the expression $(18\mathbf{c} - 14\mathbf{b}) + 13\mathbf{a}$:
\begin{align*}
(18\mathbf{c} - 14\mathbf{b}) + 13\mathbf{a} &= 18\mathbf{c} - 14\mathbf{b} + 13\mathbf{a} \\
&= 18\mathbf{c} + 13\mathbf{a} - 14\mathbf{b}.
\end{align*}

## Step 5: Using the properties of the cross product, we can find $\mathbf{a} \times (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c})$:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \times (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) &= \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 10 \\ -0 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 4: First, we will calculate the cross product of $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{b}$:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{b} &= (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}) \times \mathbf{b} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \times \mathbf{b} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 7 \mathbf{i} + 2 \mathbf{j} + 14 \mathbf{k} \\ -4 \mathbf{i} + 7 \mathbf{j} - 2 \mathbf{k} \\ -7 \mathbf{i} - 2 \mathbf{j} + 4 \mathbf{k} \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -7 \\ 14 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

## Step 2: Let's first expand the expression using the properties of the cross product. We can start by distributing the cross product operation:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 6\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}
\end{align*}
## Step 3: Next, we can simplify the expression by using the properties of the cross product:
\begin{align*}
6\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} &= 6\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}\mathbf{b}) \\
&= 6\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}
\end{align*}
## Step 4: We know that the cross product is distributive, so we can rewrite the expression as:
\begin{align*}
6\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} &= (6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} + (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c}
\end{align*}
## Step 5: Using the properties of the cross product, we can simplify the expression further:
\begin{align*}
(6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} + (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} &= (6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} - (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c}
\end{align*}
## Step 6: We can use the properties of the cross product again to simplify the expression:
\begin{align*}
(6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} - (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} &= (6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}
\end{align*}
## Step 7: Substituting the given cross product values, we get:
\begin{align*}
(6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} &= (6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} - \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
## Step 8: Expanding and simplifying, we get:
\begin{align*}
(6\mathbf{b} - 2\mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} - \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} 6\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} - 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} \\ -7\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 7\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} \\ 18\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} - 2\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 16 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
The final answer is: $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 16 \end{pmatrix}}$

## Step 3: We can write the expansion as follows:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 2 \mathbf{b} \times 3 \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{a} \times 3 \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} \\
&= 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}
\end{align*}

## Step 3: Expanding the expression, we have
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a})&=2\mathbf{b} \times 3\mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{a} \times 3\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}
\end{align*}We know that the cross product is distributive over addition, so we can simplify the expression.

## Step 3: The expression can be expanded as follows:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 2 (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) + 2 (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}) - (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}) \\
&= 2 \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} + 2 \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -14 \\ 36 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 12 \\ -14 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 2 + 12 - 4 \\ -14 - 14 + 7 \\ 36 + 6 - 2 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 10 \\ -21 \\ 40 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

## Step 20: Using the cross product property for three vectors, we can calculate this:
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{vmatrix}
\mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\
6 & -7 & 3 \\
1 & -7 & 18
\end{vmatrix} \\
&= (\mathbf{i}(18 - (-21)) - \mathbf{j}(108 - 3) + \mathbf{k}(-42 - (-7))) \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 39 \\ -105 \\ -35 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 14:  Calculating the numerical values, we get
\begin{align*}
6 \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + 2 \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ -7 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix} - 3 \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} 36 \\ -42 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} -8 \\ -14 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -21 \\ 54 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 36-8-3 \\ -42-14+21 \\ 18-4-54 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 25 \\ -55 \\ -40 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 3: Use the vector triple product identity again
Now, we can use the vector triple product identity again to simplify the expression:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (4 \mathbf{c}) + (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (\mathbf{a})\\
&=4 (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} + (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 3: Distribute the cross product
Now, we need to distribute the cross product:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 2 \mathbf{b} \times (4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) - \mathbf{a} \times (4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a})\\
&= 2 (\mathbf{b} \times 4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - (\mathbf{a} \times 4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}).
\end{align*}

## Step 4: Simplify the expression
Since $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} = \mathbf{0},$ we can simplify the expression:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 2 (\mathbf{b} \times 4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - (4\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{0})\\
&= 8 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 4 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}.
\end{align*}

## Step 5: Substitute the known values
Now, we can substitute the known values of $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b},$ $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c},$ and $\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}.$
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 8 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 4 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}\\
&= 8 \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + 2 \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} - 4 \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 4: Apply the vector triple product identity again
We can apply the vector triple product identity to the terms in the expression:
\begin{align*}
- (\mathbf{a} \times 4 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}) &= - (4 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}\mathbf{c})\\
&= - (4 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}\mathbf{c}).
\end{align*}

## Step 2: Apply the vector triple product identity
Using the identity, we can expand the given expression as follows:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 2 \mathbf{b} \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) - \mathbf{a} \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) \\
&= 2 (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) \times \mathbf{c} + 2 (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} - (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}) \times \mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 4: Simplify the remaining term using the vector triple product identity
Similarly, applying the identity to the remaining term, we get:
\begin{align*}
-(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}) \times \mathbf{a} &= - [\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}] \mathbf{c} + (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}) \mathbf{a} \\
&= -\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} + (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}) \mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 6: Conclude by combining the results of the given expression
Combining the simplified terms, we have:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 0 + 2 (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c} \\
&= 2 (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{c}.
\end{align*}

## Step 5: Continue simplifying the given expression
Since $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} = 0$, we have
\begin{align*}
- \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}) &= - 0 (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}) \\
&= 0.
\end{align*}

## Step 3: Write the expression using the vector triple product identity
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c}) + (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a} \\
&= 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 3 (2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} \\
&= 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 4: Simplify the expression using the properties of cross product
Since $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} = 0$ for any vector $\mathbf{a},$ we can simplify the expression
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} \times 3 \mathbf{c}) + (2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - (\mathbf{a} \times 3 \mathbf{c}) - (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}) &= 2(3 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) + 2(\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - (\mathbf{a} \times 3 \mathbf{c})\\
&= 6(\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) + 2(\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - 3(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}).
\end{align*}

## Step 6: Substitute the given cross products
Substituting the given cross products, we have
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 6(\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) + (2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - (\mathbf{a} \times 3 \mathbf{c})\\
&= 6\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + (2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a}) - \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

## Step 2: Apply the vector triple product identity to the given expression
We can rewrite the expression $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a})$ as
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times 3 \mathbf{c} + (2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 3: Evaluate $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times 3 \mathbf{c}$
Using the vector triple product identity, we get
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times 3 \mathbf{c} &= (2 \mathbf{b} \cdot 3 \mathbf{c})\mathbf{a} - (2 \mathbf{b} \cdot 3 \mathbf{c})\mathbf{a}\\
&= 6 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c})\mathbf{a} - 6 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{c}.
\end{align*}

## Step 4: Evaluate $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a}$
Using the vector triple product identity, we get
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a} &= (2 \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} - (2 \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{a}\\
&= 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} - 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 4: Evaluate $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a}$
Since $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} = \mathbf{0},$ we have
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a} &= 0.
\end{align*}

## Step 4: Evaluate $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a}$
Using the vector triple product identity again, we get
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a} &= (2 \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} - (2 \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{a}\\
&= 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} - 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

## Step 8: Compute $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a}$
Substitute the results of steps 3 and 5 into the expression from step 2:
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times \mathbf{a} &= 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} - 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{a} \\
&= 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} - 2 (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a})\mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

